# Unit 2 – Ecosystems
add(g,s,2,0,[p("What is a food web?","Overlapping food chains.","A diagram showing all the feeding relationships among organisms in an ecosystem.",E),p("What is a producer?","Makes own food.","An organism (usually a plant) that makes its own food through photosynthesis.",E),p("What is the difference between a herbivore and a carnivore?","Diet type.","Herbivore: eats only plants. Carnivore: eats only animals.",M),p("Describe the flow of energy in a food chain.","Producer → consumer.","Energy flows from the sun → producers → primary consumers → secondary consumers → tertiary consumers.",M),p("What happens to a food web if the population of one species suddenly declines?","Interdependence.","Other species that depend on it for food decrease; species it ate may increase — cascade effects throughout the web.",H),p("Why does energy decrease at each level of a food chain (only ~10% is passed on)?","Energy loss.","90% of energy is lost to heat, movement, and metabolism at each level — only 10% is stored in body mass for the next level.",H)])
add(g,s,2,1,[p("What is the main source of energy for most ecosystems?","The sun.","The sun (solar energy) — captured by producers through photosynthesis.",E),p("How does energy enter an ecosystem?","Photosynthesis.","Producers convert sunlight into chemical energy (glucose) through photosynthesis.",E),p("Explain the 10% energy rule.","Energy lost at each level.","Only about 10% of energy at each trophic level is passed to the next; 90% is lost as heat.",M),p("Draw a simple energy pyramid with 3 levels and label each.","Producers at base.","Base: Producers (most energy). Middle: Primary Consumers. Top: Secondary Consumers (least energy).",M),p("Why are there fewer top predators than herbivores in an ecosystem?","Energy pyramid.","Energy decreases at each level — less energy available supports fewer individuals at the top.",H),p("How does energy flow differently from nutrient cycling?","One-way vs. cyclic.","Energy flows one way (sun → producers → consumers → lost as heat); nutrients cycle continuously through the ecosystem.",H)])
add(g,s,2,2,[p("What is biodiversity?","Variety of life.","The variety of different species of plants, animals, and other organisms in an area.",E),p("Name two reasons biodiversity is important.","Benefits of variety.","Ecosystem stability, medicines, food sources, clean air/water (any two).",E),p("How does a diverse ecosystem respond better to disturbances than a less diverse one?","Multiple species fill roles.","More species means more backup — if one species is lost, others can fill its ecological role.",M),p("Give an example of a keystone species and explain its importance.","Species with large impact.","Sea otters: they eat sea urchins; without otters, urchins destroy kelp forests, affecting many other species.",M),p("How does deforestation affect biodiversity?","Habitat destruction.","Destroys habitats, eliminating many species; reduces food/shelter, fragments populations, and alters climate.",H),p("Why is it difficult to restore biodiversity once it is lost in an area?","Complex relationships.","Species depend on each other; losing one can trigger cascading extinctions, and reintroducing species requires suitable habitat and food webs.",H)])
add(g,s,2,3,[p("What is an ecosystem service?","Benefit nature provides.","A benefit that ecosystems provide to humans, such as clean air, clean water, or food.",E),p("Name one ecosystem service provided by forests.","Think trees.","Carbon storage / oxygen production / clean water filtration / habitat (any one).",E),p("How do wetlands protect coastal communities?","Natural barriers.","Wetlands absorb floodwater, filter pollutants, and act as buffers against storm surges.",M),p("Explain how bees provide an ecosystem service.","Pollination.","Bees pollinate crops and wild plants — without them, many plants cannot reproduce, affecting food supplies.",M),p("What happens to ecosystem services when natural habitats are destroyed?","Loss of services.","Services like clean water filtration, flood protection, and pollination decline — humans must then pay for artificial replacements.",H),p("Assign an economic value to one ecosystem service and explain why it's difficult to price nature.","Valuing nature.","Example: global pollination by bees is estimated at $235 billion/year; pricing is difficult because nature is priceless, complex, and irreplaceable.",H)])
add(g,s,2,4,[p("Give one example of how humans negatively impact ecosystems.","Pollution, deforestation, etc.","Pollution (plastics in oceans), deforestation, overfishing, or urban sprawl (any one).",E),p("What is habitat destruction?","Removing where organisms live.","The elimination or fragmentation of natural habitats, making it impossible for species to survive there.",E),p("How does pollution affect aquatic ecosystems?","Contaminants in water.","Pollution (chemicals, plastics, excess nutrients) can kill fish, reduce oxygen levels, and destroy food webs.",M),p("What is an invasive species? Give an example.","Non-native species that spreads.","An organism introduced to a new habitat where it has no natural predators, allowing it to out-compete native species. E.g., lionfish in Atlantic.",M),p("Describe how climate change affects ecosystems.","Temperature and precipitation shifts.","Rising temperatures shift species ranges, alter timing of seasons, cause coral bleaching, melt ice habitats, and disrupt food webs.",H),p("Propose three actions individuals can take to reduce human impact on ecosystems.","Personal actions.","Reduce energy use, eat less meat, buy sustainably sourced products, reduce single-use plastics, support conservation (any three).",H)])
# Unit 3 – Life Science
add(g,s,3,0,[p("Name the two main types of cells.","Prokaryote and eukaryote.","Prokaryotic (no nucleus) and eukaryotic (has a nucleus).",E),p("What is the function of the cell membrane?","Controls what enters/exits.","It controls what enters and exits the cell, protecting the cell's interior.",E),p("What is the difference between plant and animal cells?","Two key differences.","Plant cells have a cell wall, chloroplasts, and a large vacuole; animal cells lack these.",M),p("What is the nucleus and what does it do?","Control center.","The nucleus contains DNA and controls the cell's activities (the 'brain' of the cell).",M),p("Describe the function of mitochondria.","Energy producers.","Mitochondria produce energy (ATP) for the cell through cellular respiration — called the 'powerhouse of the cell.'",H),p("Explain why cells are so small and why multicellular organisms need many of them.","Surface area to volume ratio.","Small size gives a high surface-area-to-volume ratio for efficient nutrient/waste exchange; complex organisms need many specialized cells.",H)])
add(g,s,3,1,[p("What is photosynthesis?","Making food from sunlight.","The process by which plants use sunlight, water, and CO₂ to make glucose (sugar) and oxygen.",E),p("Write the basic equation for photosynthesis.","6+6→6+6.","6CO₂ + 6H₂O + light → C₆H₁₂O₆ + 6O₂",E),p("Where in the plant cell does photosynthesis occur?","Green organelle.","In the chloroplasts (which contain chlorophyll, the green pigment).",M),p("Why do plants appear green?","Chlorophyll reflects green.","Chlorophyll absorbs red and blue light but reflects green light — which we see.",M),p("How does photosynthesis support almost all life on Earth?","Foundation of food webs.","It converts solar energy into chemical energy (glucose) that feeds producers; all consumers ultimately depend on this energy.",H),p("Explain the relationship between photosynthesis and cellular respiration.","Opposite processes.","Photosynthesis uses CO₂ and produces O₂; cellular respiration uses O₂ and produces CO₂ — they are complementary cycles.",H)])
add(g,s,3,2,[p("What is asexual reproduction?","One parent.","Reproduction involving one parent that produces genetically identical offspring (clones).",E),p("Give two examples of asexual reproduction in living things.","Binary fission, budding.","Bacteria splitting (binary fission), yeast budding, starfish regeneration, plant runners (any two).",E),p("What is sexual reproduction and what are its advantages?","Two parents, genetic diversity.","Involves two parents combining genetic material — produces offspring with new combinations of traits, increasing genetic diversity.",M),p("Compare asexual and sexual reproduction.","One vs. two parents.","Asexual: one parent, identical offspring, faster. Sexual: two parents, varied offspring, slower but adaptable.",M),p("How does genetic variation from sexual reproduction help a species survive in changing environments?","Natural selection.","Variation means some individuals may have traits suited to new conditions — those survive and reproduce, allowing the species to adapt.",H),p("Describe how a sea anemone can reproduce both asexually and sexually.","Two strategies.","Asexually by splitting (fission) when conditions are stable; sexually by releasing eggs and sperm into the water to increase genetic variation.",H)])
add(g,s,3,3,[p("What is heredity?","Passing traits to offspring.","The passing of traits (characteristics) from parents to offspring through genes.",E),p("What are genes?","Segments of DNA.","Segments of DNA that carry instructions for specific traits (like eye color or height).",E),p("What is a dominant vs. recessive trait?","Always vs. hidden trait.","Dominant trait always shows when present; recessive trait only shows if two copies are inherited.",M),p("Define allele.","Version of a gene.","An allele is one of two or more versions of a gene — one inherited from each parent.",M),p("If a parent with BB alleles mates with a parent with bb alleles, what are the offspring's alleles?","Bb cross.","All offspring will be Bb (one dominant, one recessive allele).",H),p("Explain why two brown-eyed parents can have a blue-eyed child.","Hidden recessive alleles.","Both parents may carry a recessive allele for blue eyes (Bb × Bb); a bb offspring gets one recessive from each parent.",H)])
add(g,s,3,4,[p("What are the two main kingdoms used to classify animals?","Think vertebrates and invertebrates.","Vertebrates (have a backbone) and invertebrates (no backbone).",E),p("Name the five levels of Linnaean classification from largest to smallest.","Kingdom → Species.","Kingdom, Phylum, Class, Order, Family, Genus, Species (5 of these).",E),p("What characteristics are used to classify organisms?","Multiple features.","Physical traits, DNA/genetic similarity, reproductive methods, and evolutionary history.",M),p("How are mammals classified? Give three defining traits.","Think warm-blooded, hair, nursing.","Mammals are warm-blooded, have hair/fur, give birth to live young (usually), and nurse young with milk.",M),p("Why was the kingdom system updated to include domains?","Genetic discoveries.","DNA analysis showed prokaryotes split into two distinct domains (Bacteria and Archaea) — more accurate than a single 'Monera' kingdom.",H),p("Classify a dog using all 7 levels of taxonomy.","Canis lupus familiaris.","Domain: Eukarya, Kingdom: Animalia, Phylum: Chordata, Class: Mammalia, Order: Carnivora, Family: Canidae, Genus: Canis, Species: lupus familiaris.",H)])

# ── ELA ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
s = "ela"
# Unit 0 – Reading Literature
add(g,s,0,0,[p("What are the three main story elements?","Plot, setting, character.","Plot (what happens), setting (where/when), character (who is in the story).",E),p("What is the climax of a story?","Turning point.","The most exciting or tense moment — the turning point of the plot.",E),p("Describe the difference between a protagonist and an antagonist.","Hero vs. villain.","Protagonist: the main character (often the hero). Antagonist: the character who opposes the protagonist.",M),p("What is rising action in a story plot?","Events leading to climax.","The events and conflicts that build tension after the exposition and lead to the climax.",M),p("Analyze how the setting of a story affects the plot. Give an example.","Setting shapes events.","E.g., a story set during a blizzard forces characters to seek shelter, creating conflict that drives the plot.",H),p("How does an author develop a round (complex) character vs. a flat character?","Depth and growth.","Round: changes and has multiple traits/motivations. Flat: one-dimensional, does not change (often a minor character).",H)])
add(g,s,0,1,[p("What is the theme of a story?","Central message.","The central message or lesson the author wants readers to take away.",E),p("How is theme different from plot?","What vs. why.","Plot = what happens; theme = the deeper message or idea about life/humanity.",E),p("Identify a possible theme for a story where a character learns to be honest after lying.","Lesson learned.","Honesty is more important than temporary comfort / dishonesty has consequences.",M),p("Give two ways an author communicates theme without stating it directly.","Show don't tell.","Through character actions/decisions, recurring symbols, dialogue, consequences of events.",M),p("How can one story have multiple themes?","Complex stories.","Different readers may identify different lessons; a story about war may explore themes of courage AND the cost of conflict.",H),p("Write a theme statement (not just a topic) for a book where a child overcomes fear to save a friend.","Full statement.","Friendship gives us the courage to face our greatest fears. (Not just 'fear' — a complete idea about life.)",H)])
add(g,s,0,2,[p("What is point of view in literature?","Who tells the story.","The perspective from which a story is told.",E),p("What is first-person point of view?","I/me narration.","When the narrator is a character in the story and uses 'I' and 'me.'",E),p("Difference between third-person limited and omniscient?","One vs. all minds.","Limited: narrator knows thoughts of one character. Omniscient: narrator knows thoughts of all characters.",M),p("How does point of view affect how we understand events in a story?","Narrator's bias.","A first-person narrator can only tell what they observe/feel — we may miss information another character has.",M),p("Rewrite this sentence from third-person to first-person: 'She felt nervous about the test.'","Change pronouns.","'I felt nervous about the test.'",H),p("Why might an author choose an unreliable narrator? What effect does this create?","Reader uncertainty.","Creates mystery or irony — the reader knows the narrator may be wrong, creating suspense and making readers think critically.",H)])
add(g,s,0,3,[p("What does it mean to compare two texts?","Find similarities.","To identify ways in which two texts are alike in theme, structure, or content.",E),p("What does it mean to contrast two texts?","Find differences.","To identify ways in which two texts differ in perspective, style, or information.",E),p("Give two things you could compare between two stories.","Similar features.","Theme, character types, setting, conflict, point of view, or tone.",M),p("Two stories both feature a hero's journey but in different settings. What is the same? What differs?","Apply compare/contrast.","Same: hero faces challenge, grows, returns changed. Different: specific events, setting, cultural context.",M),p("How can comparing texts from different cultures broaden understanding of a theme?","Multiple perspectives.","Seeing how different cultures explore the same theme (e.g., courage) shows that the idea is universal but expressed differently.",H),p("Using a Venn diagram approach, compare a poem and a short story about the same topic. What would be in each section?","Structure and content differ.","Poem only: rhyme, meter, imagery. Story only: detailed plot, dialogue, characters. Overlap: theme, mood, subject.",H)])
add(g,s,0,4,[p("What is figurative language?","Non-literal language.","Language that uses words in non-literal ways to create meaning or imagery.",E),p("What is a simile? Give an example.","Comparison using like/as.","A comparison using 'like' or 'as.' Example: 'She runs like the wind.'",E),p("What is a metaphor? How is it different from a simile?","Direct comparison.","A metaphor directly states one thing IS another. 'Life is a journey' (no like/as). Simile uses like/as.",M),p("Identify the type of figurative language: 'The stars danced in the sky.'","Not literal.","Personification — giving non-human things human qualities.",M),p("Find and explain the hyperbole in: 'I've told you a million times!'","Exaggeration.","Hyperbole — extreme exaggeration for effect. They haven't literally said it a million times.",H),p("Write an original sentence using each: simile, metaphor, personification.","Create your own.","Simile: 'The fog was like a thick blanket.' Metaphor: 'The wind is a howling wolf.' Personification: 'The leaves whispered secrets to each other.'",H)])
# Unit 1 – Informational Text
add(g,s,1,0,[p("What is the main idea of a text?","Central point.","The most important point the author makes about the topic.",E),p("What are supporting details?","Evidence for main idea.","Facts, examples, or explanations that support and develop the main idea.",E),p("How do you find the main idea if it is not stated directly?","Infer from details.","Look at what most details have in common — the main idea ties them all together.",M),p("Write a main idea sentence for a paragraph about dolphins' intelligence.","One sentence summary.","Main idea: Dolphins display remarkable intelligence through problem-solving, communication, and social behavior.",M),p("Distinguish between main idea and topic.","Topic is broader.","Topic: what the text is about (one or two words). Main idea: the central point about the topic (a complete statement).",H),p("A paragraph has 5 sentences. How do you identify which are main idea vs. supporting detail?","Most general vs. specific.","Main idea = the most general statement all others support. Supporting details = specific facts, examples, stats.",H)])
add(g,s,1,1,[p("What is an author's purpose?","Why they wrote it.","The reason an author writes — to inform, to persuade, or to entertain.",E),p("Give an example of a text written to persuade.","Opinion or argument.","An editorial arguing for longer recess time at school.",E),p("How can you identify if a text is persuasive?","Look for opinion clues.","Opinion words, one-sided evidence, emotional appeals, and a call to action.",M),p("Why is it important to identify an author's purpose when reading?","Evaluate the text.","Knowing the purpose helps you evaluate whether the author is being objective or trying to influence you.",M),p("An article uses only positive facts about a product. What might the author's purpose be?","Hidden agenda.","To persuade readers to buy the product — the author may be leaving out negative information.",H),p("Compare the author's purpose in a newspaper article vs. an advertisement about the same topic.","Inform vs. sell.","Newspaper: to inform with balanced facts. Advertisement: to persuade by highlighting only positive points.",H)])
add(g,s,1,2,[p("Name three common text structures in informational writing.","How text is organized.","Cause/effect, problem/solution, compare/contrast, sequence/chronological, description (any three).",E),p("What signal words suggest a cause-and-effect text structure?","Clue words.","'because,' 'therefore,' 'as a result,' 'caused by,' 'consequently.'",E),p("Identify the text structure: 'First… then… finally…'","Order of events.","Sequence (chronological/sequential) — events in time order.",M),p("How does recognizing text structure help you read more effectively?","Predicts organization.","It helps you predict what information is coming, organize your notes, and find key ideas faster.",M),p("An article describes how pollution causes fish to die, which reduces birds, which affects plants. What structure?","Multiple cause-effects.","Cause and effect (chain reaction).",H),p("Rewrite this sentence to show compare/contrast structure: 'Cats and dogs are both good pets.'","Add differences.","'While cats are independent and low-maintenance, dogs require more attention and exercise — yet both make loyal companions.'",H)])
add(g,s,1,3,[p("What is evidence in an informational text?","Proof supporting a claim.","Facts, statistics, examples, or expert opinions that support a claim.",E),p("Why do authors use evidence in informational texts?","Build credibility.","To prove their points are accurate and reliable, not just opinions.",E),p("Distinguish between strong and weak evidence.","Quality of support.","Strong: specific, relevant, from credible sources. Weak: vague, outdated, or from biased sources.",M),p("A claim says 'Exercise improves grades.' What evidence would best support this?","Specific data.","A study showing students who exercise regularly score higher on tests, from a peer-reviewed journal.",M),p("Evaluate: Is 'My friend says this medicine works' strong evidence? Why or why not?","Personal anecdote.","Weak — anecdotal, not from a credible or scientific source.",H),p("An author claims climate change is a serious problem. List three types of evidence they could use.","Variety of evidence.","Temperature data over decades, scientific consensus reports, evidence of rising sea levels / species extinction (any three).",H)])
add(g,s,1,4,[p("What is summarizing?","Retell the main points.","Restating the most important ideas of a text in your own words, briefly.",E),p("What should a summary NOT include?","Avoid these.","Unimportant details, personal opinions, or direct quotes (unless essential).",E),p("Summarize this: 'Dogs are loyal pets. They protect homes. They need exercise and care.'","One concise sentence.","Dogs make loyal, protective pets that require proper exercise and care.",M),p("What is the difference between a summary and a paraphrase?","Length and scope.","Summary: shorter, covers whole text's main ideas. Paraphrase: same length, restates specific passage in your own words.",M),p("Write a 2-sentence summary of a 5-paragraph article about recycling's benefits.","Hit the key points.","Recycling reduces landfill waste and conserves natural resources. It also lowers pollution and saves energy compared to producing new materials.",H),p("How do you determine which details to include in a summary?","Ask: essential to meaning?","Include only ideas that are necessary to understand the main point; leave out examples, minor details, and repetition.",H)])
# Unit 2 – Writing
add(g,s,2,0,[p("What is the purpose of narrative writing?","Tell a story.","To tell a real or fictional story that entertains, reflects, or shares an experience.",E),p("Name three elements of a good narrative.","Story parts.","Engaging opening, vivid details/characters, a clear conflict and resolution.",E),p("What is 'show, don't tell' in writing?","Specific details.","Instead of saying 'she was sad,' describe her behavior: 'She stared at the floor, tears silently sliding down her cheeks.'",M),p("Write a strong opening sentence for a story about getting lost in the woods.","Hook the reader.","'The last thing I heard before the trail disappeared was the crunch of my own footsteps — and then silence.'",M),p("How does dialogue improve a narrative?","Characters speaking.","Dialogue reveals character personality, moves the plot, and makes the story feel real and engaging.",H),p("Revise this weak narrative sentence: 'It was a dark and scary night.'","Add sensory detail.","'Clouds swallowed the moon whole, and the only sounds were the wind through bare branches and the distant howl of something I couldn't name.'",H)])
add(g,s,2,1,[p("What is the purpose of informational/explanatory writing?","Explain or inform.","To explain a topic clearly using facts, definitions, and examples.",E),p("Name the three main parts of an informational essay.","Essay structure.","Introduction, body paragraphs, conclusion.",E),p("What should an introduction include?","Opening requirements.","A hook (opening), background information, and a thesis statement.",M),p("Write a thesis statement for an essay about why school should start later.","One clear claim.","'Schools should start at 8:30 a.m. or later because teenagers need more sleep for better health and academic performance.'",M),p("How does using transition words improve informational writing?","Sentence flow.","Transitions (first, however, in addition, therefore) connect ideas and help readers follow the logic.",H),p("Explain why evidence must be specific in an informational essay. Give an example.","Vague vs. specific.","Vague: 'Many students are tired.' Specific: 'A 2019 study found that 70% of teens get less than the recommended 8 hours of sleep on school nights.'",H)])
add(g,s,2,2,[p("What is the goal of argument writing?","Persuade with evidence.","To convince readers to agree with a claim using logical evidence and reasoning.",E),p("What is a claim in argument writing?","The writer's position.","A clear statement of the writer's position or opinion on an issue.",E),p("What is a counterclaim and why is it important?","Opposing view.","A counterclaim acknowledges the other side's argument; addressing it shows fairness and strengthens your own position.",M),p("Write a claim statement for the argument that homework should be limited.","One sentence.","'Students perform better when homework is limited to 30 minutes per night per subject.'",M),p("How do you respond to a counterclaim effectively?","Refute or concede.","Acknowledge the opposing point, then explain why your evidence outweighs it (refutation or concession+rebuttal).",H),p("Identify the logical fallacy: 'Everyone is getting a cell phone, so I should too.'","Type of fallacy.","Bandwagon fallacy — doing something because 'everyone' does it is not logical evidence.",H)])
add(g,s,2,3,[p("What is a reliable source for research?","Where to look.","A source that is accurate, credible, current, and from an expert or reputable organization.",E),p("Name two places to find reliable information for a research paper.","Libraries and databases.","Library databases, academic journals, reputable news organizations, government websites (.gov).",E),p("Why should you use multiple sources for research?","Avoid bias.","Using multiple sources helps verify information and gives a more complete, balanced view.",M),p("What is plagiarism and how do you avoid it?","Copying without credit.","Using someone else's words or ideas without credit. Avoid by quoting, paraphrasing, and citing sources.",M),p("Evaluate this source: 'A blog post by an anonymous writer claims vaccines cause disease.' Reliable?","Check credibility.","Not reliable — anonymous source, contradicts scientific consensus, no credentials given.",H),p("Explain the difference between quoting, paraphrasing, and summarizing a source.","Three ways to use sources.","Quote: exact words in quotation marks. Paraphrase: restate specific idea in your own words. Summarize: condense whole source's main points.",H)])
add(g,s,2,4,[p("What is the revision step in the writing process?","Improve the draft.","Re-reading and improving content, organization, clarity, and style of a draft.",E),p("What is editing?","Fix surface errors.","Correcting grammar, spelling, punctuation, and capitalization errors.",E),p("What is the difference between revising and editing?","Content vs. conventions.","Revising = improving ideas, organization, detail. Editing = fixing language/mechanical errors.",M),p("Give three questions to ask yourself when revising an essay.","Self-review prompts.","Is my thesis clear? Is my evidence specific? Are my ideas logically ordered? (any three)",M),p("Why is it helpful to read your writing aloud during revision?","Hear the writing.","You catch awkward phrasing, missing words, and unclear sentences more easily when you hear them.",H),p("A peer reviewer says: 'Your conclusion just repeats the intro.' How do you revise it?","Synthesis, not repetition.","A strong conclusion synthesizes ideas and ends with a broader insight or call to action — not just a copy of the introduction.",H)])
# Unit 3 – Language Conventions
add(g,s,3,0,[p("Name the eight parts of speech.","Grammar basics.","Noun, verb, adjective, adverb, pronoun, preposition, conjunction, interjection.",E),p("What does an adverb modify?","Describe verbs/adjectives.","An adverb modifies a verb, adjective, or another adverb (e.g., 'runs quickly').",E),p("Identify the nouns and verbs: 'The dog chased the ball.'","Label each word.","Nouns: dog, ball. Verb: chased.",M),p("What is a pronoun? Give three examples.","Replaces a noun.","A word that replaces a noun. Examples: he, she, they, it, we, I (any three).",M),p("Identify the conjunctions: 'I like pizza and pasta, but I don't eat seafood.'","Connecting words.","'and' connects pizza/pasta; 'but' connects the two clauses.",H),p("Explain the difference between a preposition and a conjunction with examples.","Function difference.","Preposition: shows relationship ('in the box,' 'under the table'). Conjunction: connects words/clauses ('and,' 'because,' 'although').",H)])
add(g,s,3,1,[p("What is a complete sentence?","Subject + predicate.","A sentence with a subject (who/what) and a predicate (verb + other info) that expresses a complete thought.",E),p("Identify the subject and predicate: 'The tall tree swayed in the wind.'","Label each part.","Subject: The tall tree. Predicate: swayed in the wind.",E),p("What is a compound sentence?","Two independent clauses.","Two independent clauses joined by a coordinating conjunction (FANBOYS) or semicolon.",M),p("What is a complex sentence?","Independent + dependent.","An independent clause joined to a dependent clause with a subordinating conjunction (because, although, when, etc.).",M),p("Fix the sentence fragment: 'Running through the park.'","Add subject and verb.","'She was running through the park.'",H),p("Combine into one complex sentence: 'It rained. We stayed inside.'","Add subordinating conjunction.","'Because it rained, we stayed inside.' or 'We stayed inside because it rained.'",H)])
add(g,s,3,2,[p("When do you use a comma before a coordinating conjunction?","Compound sentences.","When joining two independent clauses: 'I like cats, and she likes dogs.'",E),p("When does a sentence end with a question mark?","Direct questions.","When it asks a direct question: 'Where are you going?'",E),p("When should you use a semicolon?","Joining related clauses.","To join two related independent clauses without a conjunction: 'I love reading; my sister prefers painting.'",M),p("Correct the punctuation: 'We went to the store we bought milk eggs and bread.'","Add punctuation.","'We went to the store; we bought milk, eggs, and bread.'",M),p("Explain three rules for using commas correctly.","Comma rules.","1) In a list. 2) After an introductory clause. 3) Before a coordinating conjunction in a compound sentence.",H),p("Insert correct punctuation: 'Although the rain was heavy the game continued fans cheered the players on.'","Multiple corrections.","'Although the rain was heavy, the game continued; fans cheered the players on.'",H)])
add(g,s,3,3,[p("What is the best way to expand your vocabulary?","Reading and exposure.","Reading widely, using context clues, looking up unfamiliar words, and using a thesaurus.",E),p("What is a synonym?","Same meaning.","A word that has the same or similar meaning as another word. Example: happy/joyful.",E),p("What is a connotation?","Emotional meaning.","The emotional or cultural meaning of a word beyond its literal definition. E.g., 'slender' vs. 'skinny.'",M),p("Find two synonyms for 'happy' with different connotations.","Shade of meaning.","'Cheerful' (bright, outgoing) vs. 'content' (calm, satisfied) — both positive but feel different.",M),p("Explain how context clues help you figure out an unknown word's meaning.","Context strategies.","Using the surrounding words, sentences, and topic to infer what an unfamiliar word likely means.",H),p("The word 'perambulate' appears in a story about a baby carriage. What does it likely mean?","Root and context.","To walk or travel slowly. (Latin: per=through + ambulare=walk); context of a baby carriage confirms movement.",H)])
add(g,s,3,4,[p("What is a context clue?","Hints in surrounding text.","Words, phrases, or sentences near an unknown word that help you figure out its meaning.",E),p("Use the context clue: 'She was ravenous — she hadn't eaten in two days.' What does ravenous mean?","Look at explanation after dash.","Extremely hungry.",E),p("Identify the type of context clue: 'The tenacious, or determined, athlete never gave up.'","Definition clue.","Definition clue — the author defines the word right after it.",M),p("How do you use antonym clues? Give an example.","Opposite is given.","'Unlike the timid mouse, the cat was audacious.' Timid = shy → audacious = bold/daring.",M),p("Use root words to guess the meaning of 'bilateral.'","Bi = two, lateral = side.","Having or relating to two sides.",H),p("A text says: 'The politician used obfuscating language, making his real intentions impossible to understand.' What does obfuscating mean?","Context from result.","Making something confusing or unclear — the context shows the result (impossible to understand).",H)])
# Unit 4 – Speaking & Listening
add(g,s,4,0,[p("What are two important rules for a productive group discussion?","Respectful participation.","Listen without interrupting; build on others' ideas respectfully.",E),p("Why is it important to take turns speaking in a discussion?","Fairness and hearing everyone.","So everyone gets a chance to share, and all perspectives can be heard and considered.",E),p("How can you respectfully disagree with someone in a discussion?","Polite disagreement.","'I understand your point, but I think…' — acknowledge their view first, then explain your own.",M),p("What does an effective discussion participant do when they don't understand something?","Ask for clarification.","Ask a clarifying question: 'Could you explain what you mean by…?'",M),p("Describe two ways to prepare for a class discussion on a reading.","Pre-discussion prep.","Read the text carefully; write down key points and questions; note evidence that supports your ideas.",H),p("How do you know if a collaborative discussion is successful?","Outcomes.","Everyone participates, ideas build on each other, the group reaches a deeper understanding, and participants feel heard.",H)])
add(g,s,4,1,[p("Name two things a good presentation includes.","Presentation basics.","A clear purpose and organized structure; engaging delivery (eye contact, clear voice).",E),p("What is the most important thing to do when preparing a presentation?","Know your content.","Know your topic thoroughly so you can speak confidently without reading word-for-word.",E),p("How does eye contact improve a presentation?","Connect with audience.","It builds trust, engages the audience, and shows the speaker is confident and prepared.",M),p("What is the difference between speaking notes and a written script for a presentation?","Notes vs. full script.","Notes: key points/cues that guide natural speaking. Script: word-for-word text — reading it makes delivery feel stiff.",M),p("Design a one-minute presentation outline about your favorite book.","Structure it.","1. Hook + title/author. 2. Brief summary (avoid spoilers). 3. Why you recommend it. 4. Closing invitation to read.",H),p("Evaluate: What makes a presentation ineffective? Name three things to avoid.","Common mistakes.","Reading directly from notes, speaking too fast, no eye contact, unclear organization, not knowing the material (any three).",H)])
add(g,s,4,2,[p("What does it mean to 'evaluate' a speaker's argument?","Judge the reasoning.","To assess whether the speaker's claims are supported by strong evidence and logical reasoning.",E),p("What question should you ask about a speaker's evidence?","Evaluate the source.","Is this evidence credible, relevant, and sufficient to support the claim?",E),p("A speaker claims 'all teenagers are irresponsible' — what is wrong with this argument?","Overgeneralization.","It's an overgeneralization (hasty generalization) — one claim cannot apply to all teenagers.",M),p("How can you tell if a speaker is being persuasive vs. informative?","Intent and evidence.","Persuasive: one-sided, emotional appeals, opinion. Informative: balanced, factual, neutral tone.",M),p("Identify the appeal in: 'As a doctor with 20 years of experience, I can tell you this medicine works.'","Ethos.","Ethos — appeal to authority/credibility.",H),p("A speaker uses only extreme examples to make a policy seem necessary. What should you ask?","Cherry-picking.","Are these examples typical or are they cherry-picked? What does the data show across all cases?",H)])
add(g,s,4,3,[p("What is multimedia in a presentation?","Multiple formats.","Using different formats (video, images, audio, graphs) alongside spoken words to convey information.",E),p("Give an example of multimedia that could improve a presentation about climate change.","Visual support.","A graph showing temperature rise over 100 years, or a short video clip of melting glaciers.",E),p("When does multimedia enhance a presentation vs. distract from it?","Strategic use.","Enhances: when it clarifies or adds information. Distracts: when it's too flashy, unrelated, or replaces the speaker's message.",M),p("What makes a slide effective in a presentation?","Slide design principles.","Minimal text, large readable font, relevant visuals, clear title — supports the speaker, doesn't replace them.",M),p("Design a three-slide outline for a presentation on water conservation using multimedia.","Plan each slide.","Slide 1: Title + photo of drought. Slide 2: Data graph of water use trends. Slide 3: Three action steps + video link.",H),p("Evaluate: A student fills slides with paragraphs of text and reads them aloud. What should they change?","Critique and improve.","Replace paragraphs with bullet points or visuals; practice speaking from memory using slides as prompts only.",H)])

