# Unit 0 – Early Civilizations
add(g,s,0,0,[p("Where was Mesopotamia located?","Between two rivers.","Between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers (modern-day Iraq).",E),p("What was the world's first writing system?","Mesopotamian script.","Cuneiform — developed by the Sumerians of Mesopotamia around 3200 BCE.",E),p("What was the Code of Hammurabi?","Ancient law code.","One of the earliest written law codes, created by Babylonian King Hammurabi around 1754 BCE.",M),p("How did geography influence the development of Mesopotamian civilization?","Rivers = agriculture.","Rivers provided water for irrigation, allowing agriculture; flooding deposited fertile silt for farming.",M),p("Compare city-states in Mesopotamia to modern cities.","Ancient vs. modern city gov.","Mesopotamian city-states were self-governing, each with its own ruler and laws, similar to modern city governments — but without communication networks.",H),p("Why is Mesopotamia often called the 'Cradle of Civilization'?","First major civilization.","It developed the world's first writing, cities, governments, and formal laws — foundational achievements for all later civilizations.",H)])
add(g,s,0,1,[p("Along what river did ancient Egypt develop?","Nile River.","The Nile River.",E),p("What were the pyramids built for?","Royal tombs.","As tombs for pharaohs and symbols of royal power.",E),p("What was the role of the pharaoh in ancient Egypt?","God-king ruler.","The pharaoh was both the political ruler and a god-like religious figure — absolute authority over Egypt.",M),p("How did the Nile River support Egyptian civilization?","Flooding and farming.","Annual flooding deposited rich silt, enabling agriculture; the river also provided transportation and trade routes.",M),p("Compare the social hierarchy of ancient Egypt from top to bottom.","Class structure.","Pharaoh → priests and nobles → scribes → craftspeople/merchants → farmers → slaves.",H),p("What is hieroglyphics and why was it important?","Egyptian writing.","Egyptian picture-based writing system; important for recording history, religious texts, and government records — key to our understanding of Egyptian civilization.",H)])
add(g,s,0,2,[p("Name one ancient civilization of India.","Indus Valley.","The Indus Valley Civilization (Harappan) — flourished ~2600–1900 BCE.",E),p("What was the Silk Road?","Ancient trade route.","A network of trade routes connecting China to the Mediterranean world for goods and ideas.",E),p("Compare early Indian and Chinese civilizations — one similarity and one difference.","Compare key features.","Similarity: both had writing systems and river-based agriculture. Difference: India had the caste system; China had dynastic emperor rule.",M),p("How did geography shape early Chinese civilization?","Mountains and rivers.","Geographic barriers (mountains, deserts) isolated China, fostering unique development; Yellow River provided fertile farmland.",M),p("How did trade on the Silk Road spread not just goods but ideas?","Cultural diffusion.","Merchants brought not only silk and spices but also religions (Buddhism), technology (paper, gunpowder), and artistic styles.",H),p("Evaluate the achievements of the Indus Valley Civilization.","Urban planning.","Advanced city planning (grid streets, drainage systems), standardized weights and measures — remarkable for 2500 BCE.",H)])
add(g,s,0,3,[p("What form of government did ancient Athens develop?","Early democracy.","A direct democracy where citizens voted on laws and decisions.",E),p("Who were the major Greek philosophers?","Great thinkers.","Socrates, Plato, and Aristotle — they laid the foundations of Western philosophy.",E),p("What were the Olympic Games and why were they held?","Ancient festival.","Athletic competitions held every four years in Olympia to honor the god Zeus; began ~776 BCE.",M),p("Compare the governments of Athens and Sparta.","Two Greek city-states.","Athens: democracy, valued education and arts. Sparta: military oligarchy, valued strength and discipline.",M),p("How did Greek philosophy influence later Western civilization?","Ideas spread.","Greek ideas about reason, democracy, and logic formed the basis of Western science, government, and philosophy through the Roman Empire and Renaissance.",H),p("Analyze Alexander the Great's impact on spreading Greek culture.","Hellenism.","His conquests spread Greek language, art, and ideas from Greece to Egypt and India — creating a blended Hellenistic culture.",H)])
add(g,s,0,4,[p("What form of government was the Roman Republic?","Elected representatives.","A republic where citizens elected representatives (senators) to make laws.",E),p("Who were Julius Caesar and Augustus?","Roman leaders.","Caesar: general who became dictator; Augustus: first Roman emperor after Caesar's assassination.",E),p("How did Rome transition from a republic to an empire?","Power shift.","Civil wars weakened the republic; Caesar then Augustus seized power, creating the Roman Empire.",M),p("Name three Roman contributions to Western civilization.","Rome's legacy.","Law systems, Latin language (basis of Romance languages), engineering (roads, aqueducts), Christianity's spread (any three).",M),p("Why did the Western Roman Empire fall in 476 CE? Give two reasons.","Multiple causes.","Military pressure from Germanic tribes, political instability, economic decline, over-extended borders (any two).",H),p("How did the Pax Romana ('Roman Peace') benefit the empire?","200 years of stability.","~200 years of relative peace and stability allowed trade, road-building, and cultural exchange across a vast territory.",H)])
# Unit 1 – World Geography
add(g,s,1,0,[p("What is the difference between a map and a globe?","Flat vs. round.","A globe is a spherical model of Earth (accurate but hard to use); a map is a flat representation (easier to use but has distortions).",E),p("What is a map key (legend)?","Symbols explained.","A list that explains what symbols, colors, and lines on a map represent.",E),p("What does the map scale tell you?","Distance on map.","It shows the relationship between distance on the map and actual distance on Earth.",M),p("What are lines of latitude and longitude?","Grid system.","Latitude: horizontal lines measuring distance north/south of the equator. Longitude: vertical lines measuring east/west of the prime meridian.",M),p("Explain how to find a location using latitude and longitude.","Coordinate system.","State the latitude (N/S) first, then longitude (E/W). E.g., 40°N, 74°W is New York City.",H),p("Why are there different types of maps (political, physical, thematic)?","Different purposes.","Each shows different information — political shows borders/cities, physical shows terrain, thematic shows specific data like population or climate.",H)])
add(g,s,1,1,[p("What is physical geography?","Natural features of Earth.","The study of Earth's natural features — mountains, rivers, oceans, climate, and landforms.",E),p("Name three major types of landforms.","Earth's surface features.","Mountains, valleys, plains, plateaus, deserts, islands (any three).",E),p("How does a mountain range affect nearby climate?","Rain shadow effect.","Mountains force air upward — one side gets rain (windward), the other stays dry (rain shadow/leeward).",M),p("What causes deserts to form?","Little precipitation.","Distance from moisture sources, rain shadow effects, or atmospheric pressure patterns that prevent rainfall.",M),p("Compare a delta and an alluvial plain.","Where sediment deposits.","Delta: sediment deposited at a river's mouth (into sea). Alluvial plain: sediment deposited where a river slows on flat land.",H),p("How do plate tectonics create mountains and ocean trenches?","Convergent plates.","Converging plates push rock upward (mountains) or one plate dips below creating deep trenches.",H)])
add(g,s,1,2,[p("What is human geography?","How humans use the land.","The study of how humans interact with, use, and shape their environment.",E),p("Give two examples of how people adapt to their environment.","Adapting to climate.","Building homes suited to climate (igloos in arctic, stilts in flood zones) or growing food suited to local conditions.",E),p("What is urbanization?","Movement to cities.","The process of more people moving from rural to urban areas (cities growing).",M),p("How does a country's geography affect its economic activities?","Geography shapes economy.","Coastal nations develop fishing/trade; fertile plains → agriculture; mountains → mining or tourism.",M),p("Analyze how the physical geography of Egypt shapes where its population lives.","Nile River.","~90% of Egyptians live along the Nile River Valley/Delta — the only fertile area in an otherwise desert country.",H),p("How does globalization connect human geography across continents?","Economic links.","Trade, migration, and technology connect human activities worldwide — a drought in one country affects food prices globally.",H)])
add(g,s,1,3,[p("Name the seven continents.","All of them.","Africa, Antarctica, Asia, Australia, Europe, North America, South America.",E),p("What is a region?","Grouped by features.","An area defined by shared characteristics — physical, cultural, economic, or political.",E),p("Describe two characteristics that define a region.","Defining a region.","Shared climate, language, government, religion, or physical features (any two).",M),p("How are the regions of North Africa and Sub-Saharan Africa different?","Physical and cultural.","North Africa: mostly desert, Arabic culture, Islam. Sub-Saharan Africa: more diverse terrain, many ethnic groups and languages.",M),p("Explain how cultural regions and political boundaries sometimes conflict.","Drawn lines vs. people.","Colonial borders often split cultural groups or combined rivals — e.g., African borders drawn by Europeans without regard for ethnic groups.",H),p("How is the concept of 'region' useful in geography?","Organizing the world.","Grouping places with shared features helps us understand patterns, compare areas, and study how human and physical systems interact.",H)])
add(g,s,1,4,[p("Name two geographic tools besides maps.","Tools geographers use.","GIS (Geographic Information Systems), GPS, satellite images, aerial photographs.",E),p("What does a compass rose show on a map?","Directions.","The cardinal directions: North, South, East, West (and often intermediate directions).",E),p("How does GIS (Geographic Information Systems) help geographers?","Layered data.","GIS overlays multiple data layers (population, roads, climate) on digital maps for complex analysis.",M),p("What is remote sensing?","Collecting data from afar.","Gathering data about Earth's surface using satellites or aircraft without direct physical contact.",M),p("How might a geographer use GPS to study animal migration?","Tracking movement.","GPS collars on animals record precise location data over time — showing migration routes, distances, and habitat use.",H),p("Explain how satellite imagery has changed our understanding of Earth.","Modern technology.","Satellites reveal deforestation, ice sheet changes, urban growth, and ocean temperatures — providing data impossible to gather otherwise.",H)])
# Unit 2 – Government & Civics
add(g,s,2,0,[p("Name two types of government.","How countries are ruled.","Democracy, monarchy, dictatorship, republic, oligarchy (any two).",E),p("What is democracy?","Rule by the people.","A system where citizens have the power to choose their leaders, usually through voting.",E),p("Compare direct and representative democracy.","Two types of democracy.","Direct: citizens vote on every issue. Representative: citizens elect officials to vote on their behalf.",M),p("What is a monarchy?","Rule by a king/queen.","A system of government where a king or queen holds supreme power, often inherited.",M),p("Compare the advantages of democracy vs. dictatorship.","Benefits of each system.","Democracy: protects rights, reflects citizen preferences. Dictatorship: can make fast decisions, enforce order — but at the cost of freedom.",H),p("Why is it important that citizens understand different types of government?","Civic literacy.","Understanding systems helps citizens recognize what rights they have, evaluate their own government, and protect their freedoms.",H)])
add(g,s,2,1,[p("Why do societies need laws?","Order and fairness.","Laws protect individual rights, provide order, resolve conflicts, and ensure everyone is treated fairly.",E),p("What is the difference between a law and a rule?","Formal vs. informal.","Laws are formal, enforced by government with penalties. Rules are informal guidelines (classroom rules, house rules).",E),p("Give an example of a law and explain its purpose.","Real law.","Speed limits: protect people's safety by preventing dangerous driving.",M),p("What happens when someone breaks the law?","Consequences.","They may face fines, community service, probation, or imprisonment — depending on the severity.",M),p("Why is it important that laws apply equally to everyone, including government leaders?","Rule of law.","Equal application prevents tyranny — if leaders are above the law, they can abuse power without accountability.",H),p("How can unfair laws be changed in a democracy?","Democratic process.","Citizens vote, petition, protest, contact elected representatives, or take cases to court to challenge and change laws.",H)])
add(g,s,2,2,[p("What are rights?","Freedoms protected by law.","Freedoms or entitlements that individuals are protected to exercise (e.g., free speech, right to vote).",E),p("What is a responsibility of citizenship?","Duties of citizens.","Voting, paying taxes, obeying laws, serving on juries, staying informed (any one).",E),p("What is the Bill of Rights?","First ten amendments.","The first ten amendments to the US Constitution, protecting individual freedoms like speech, religion, and assembly.",M),p("Why do rights come with responsibilities?","Balance of freedom.","Exercising your rights while respecting others requires responsibility — free speech doesn't allow harm to others.",M),p("Give an example of a conflict between two rights.","Rights in tension.","Freedom of speech vs. protection from defamation: you can express opinions, but cannot make false statements that damage someone's reputation.",H),p("How do rights and responsibilities differ between US citizens and non-citizens?","Citizenship status.","Citizens have full rights (voting, passport) and responsibilities (jury duty, taxes). Non-citizens have many rights (due process) but not all (can't vote).",H)])
add(g,s,2,3,[p("What are democratic principles?","Core values of democracy.","Majority rule, minority rights, individual liberty, free elections, rule of law, separation of powers.",E),p("What is the separation of powers?","Three branches.","Dividing government into three branches (legislative, executive, judicial) so no single branch is too powerful.",E),p("What is checks and balances?","Branches limit each other.","Each branch of government has powers to limit the others — prevents any one branch from gaining too much power.",M),p("Why is majority rule important, but not without limits?","Minority rights.","Majority rule allows democratic decision-making, but without minority rights, majorities could oppress smaller groups.",M),p("How do free and fair elections support democratic principles?","Foundation of democracy.","They ensure leaders reflect citizens' choices, allow peaceful transfers of power, and hold leaders accountable.",H),p("Evaluate how the US Constitution puts democratic principles into practice.","Apply the principles.","Separation of powers (3 branches), checks and balances, Bill of Rights (individual liberties), elected representatives — all reflect democratic principles.",H)])
add(g,s,2,4,[p("What is local government?","Closest level of government.","Government at the city, county, or town level that deals with local issues.",E),p("Name two services provided by local government.","Local services.","Public schools, police/fire departments, roads, parks, trash collection (any two).",E),p("How is local government structured in most US cities?","Mayor and council.","A mayor (executive) and city council (legislative) — some use a city manager instead of a mayor.",M),p("Why is local government important to everyday life?","Most direct impact.","Local government affects daily life most directly — schools, roads, safety, zoning.",M),p("Compare the powers of local, state, and federal government.","Three levels.","Federal: national defense, currency, foreign policy. State: education, driver's licenses, courts. Local: zoning, public safety, utilities.",H),p("How can citizens participate in local government beyond voting?","Civic engagement.","Attend town halls, serve on school boards, contact representatives, join advisory committees, petition local officials.",H)])

