# Unit 0 – Digital Literacy
add(g,s,0,0,[p("What is one rule for staying safe online?","Protect personal info.","Never share personal information (full name, address, school) with strangers online.",E),p("What is a strong password?","Hard to guess.","A mix of uppercase, lowercase letters, numbers, and symbols — at least 8 characters.",E),p("Why should you not click on unfamiliar links in emails?","Phishing.","Links may lead to malicious sites that steal your information or install malware (phishing attacks).",M),p("What is cyberbullying and what should you do if it happens to you?","Online harassment.","Bullying through digital platforms — tell a trusted adult, block the bully, and keep evidence.",M),p("Explain why sharing passwords is unsafe even with friends.","Trust and security.","Friends may accidentally expose it; friendships end; they could share it further — passwords should be private.",H),p("Create a checklist of five internet safety rules for a younger student.","Apply safety knowledge.","1) Never share personal info. 2) Use strong passwords. 3) Tell an adult if uncomfortable. 4) Don't meet online strangers. 5) Think before you post.",H)])
add(g,s,0,1,[p("What does it mean to evaluate an online source?","Check credibility.","To determine if a website or article is trustworthy, accurate, and unbiased.",E),p("Name one thing to check when evaluating a website.","Check the author.","Who wrote it (author credentials), when it was published, and whether the organization is reputable.",E),p("Why might a .com website be less reliable than a .gov or .edu site?","Domain types.","Commercial .com sites may have a profit motive; .gov (government) and .edu (education) sites are typically more authoritative.",M),p("What is bias in a source?","One-sided view.","When a source presents only one perspective or leaves out information to influence the reader.",M),p("Analyze: An article about climate change is published by a coal company. Is it reliable?","Consider the source.","Likely biased — the coal company has a financial interest in downplaying climate risks. Look for independent scientific sources.",H),p("Describe the CRAAP test (Currency, Relevance, Authority, Accuracy, Purpose) for evaluating sources.","Evaluation framework.","Check: How recent? Is it relevant to your topic? Who wrote it? Is the info accurate and cited? Why was it written?",H)])
add(g,s,0,2,[p("What is digital citizenship?","Responsible online behavior.","Using technology responsibly, ethically, and safely.",E),p("Give an example of being a good digital citizen.","Positive digital behavior.","Giving credit when sharing others' content, not spreading rumors online, or supporting others being bullied online.",E),p("Why is it important to think before posting anything online?","Permanent record.","Once posted, content is very hard to fully remove and can affect your reputation now and in the future.",M),p("What is copyright and how does it apply to online content?","Intellectual property.","Copyright protects creators' work — you cannot use music, images, or text without permission or proper credit.",M),p("A student copies an image from Google and uses it in a school project without credit. Is this acceptable?","Citation needed.","The image should be credited to its creator; using Creative Commons or public domain images is better practice.",H),p("Design three norms for a classroom's digital citizenship policy.","Class tech rules.","1) Credit all sources. 2) Use respectful language online. 3) Only access approved sites on school devices. (any three reasonable norms)",H)])
add(g,s,0,3,[p("What is personal data?","Your private info.","Information about you — name, birthday, location, browsing habits, photos.",E),p("What is a privacy setting on social media?","Controlling access.","A feature that lets you control who can see your profile, posts, or personal information.",E),p("Why do apps ask for permission to access your location or contacts?","Data collection.","They want to collect data to personalize ads or improve services — but it's important to only grant necessary permissions.",M),p("What is data encryption?","Protecting data.","Converting data into a code so only authorized users can read it (like HTTPS websites).",M),p("A website offers a 'free' service. What might the real cost be?","Data as currency.","Your data — the company may collect and sell your personal information or browsing behavior.",H),p("Explain how reading privacy policies helps you protect your data online.","Know the terms.","Privacy policies state what data is collected and how it's used — reading them helps you make informed decisions about using services.",H)])
add(g,s,0,4,[p("What is a healthy amount of daily screen time for a 6th grader?","Balance digital and real life.","Experts recommend ≤2 hours of recreational screen time per day; balance with physical activity and sleep.",E),p("How can too much screen time affect your health?","Side effects.","Eye strain, poor sleep (especially from blue light before bed), reduced physical activity, and social disconnection.",E),p("What is digital well-being?","Healthy tech balance.","Using technology in ways that support rather than harm your mental, physical, and social health.",M),p("Describe two strategies to reduce screen time.","Practical solutions.","Set daily limits; designate 'no phone' times (meals, bedtime); use screen time tracking apps.",M),p("How does social media affect self-esteem in teens?","Comparison and validation.","Comparing yourself to others' highlights can lower self-esteem; seeking likes can create anxiety — awareness helps manage these effects.",H),p("Create a personal 'digital wellness plan' with three specific strategies.","Apply the concept.","1) No phone after 9 PM. 2) Max 90 min social media daily. 3) One 'offline' hobby per week. (Any three realistic strategies)",H)])
# Unit 1 – Introduction to Coding
add(g,s,1,0,[p("What is an algorithm?","Step-by-step instructions.","A set of step-by-step instructions for solving a problem or completing a task.",E),p("What is a flowchart?","Visual algorithm.","A diagram that uses shapes and arrows to show the steps and decisions in an algorithm.",E),p("Write a 3-step algorithm for making a sandwich.","Daily task as algorithm.","1. Get bread. 2. Add filling. 3. Put second slice on top.",M),p("In a flowchart, what shape is used for a decision?","Diamond shape.","A diamond (rhombus) shape — representing a yes/no question.",M),p("What is the difference between an algorithm and a program?","Steps vs. code.","An algorithm is the plan/logic; a program is the algorithm written in a programming language a computer can run.",H),p("Design a flowchart to decide whether to bring an umbrella based on weather.","Decision logic.","Start → Check weather → If rainy: bring umbrella → end. If not rainy: don't bring umbrella → end.",H)])
add(g,s,1,1,[p("What is sequence in programming?","Order of steps.","Instructions executed in a specific order, one after another.",E),p("What is selection (if-statement) in programming?","Decision making.","Code that executes different paths based on a condition — e.g., 'if' something is true, do this; 'else' do that.",E),p("What is iteration (loop) in programming?","Repeating actions.","Code that repeats a set of instructions a certain number of times or until a condition is met.",M),p("Write pseudocode using sequence, selection, and iteration to print numbers 1–10, but skip 5.","Combine all three.","FOR i = 1 to 10: IF i ≠ 5: PRINT i",M),p("What is an infinite loop and why should you avoid it?","Loop that never ends.","A loop with no stopping condition — it runs forever, crashing or freezing the program.",H),p("Explain the difference between a 'for loop' and a 'while loop.'","Two loop types.","For loop: runs a set number of times. While loop: runs as long as a condition is true.",H)])
add(g,s,1,2,[p("What is Scratch?","Block-based language.","A block-based visual programming language designed for beginners (by MIT).",E),p("In Scratch, what does the 'move 10 steps' block do?","Movement command.","Moves the sprite (character) forward 10 steps in the direction it is facing.",E),p("What is a sprite in Scratch?","Programmable character.","The character or object you program in Scratch.",M),p("How do you make a sprite say something for 2 seconds in Scratch?","Say block.","Use the 'say [Hello!] for 2 seconds' block in the Looks category.",M),p("Write the Scratch logic (in words) for a sprite that moves right 10 steps, turns 90°, and repeats 4 times.","Square-drawing logic.","Repeat 4: [Move 10 steps] [Turn right 90 degrees] — this draws a square.",H),p("How does using Scratch help you learn real programming concepts?","Transfer of skills.","Scratch teaches sequence, loops, conditionals, and events — the same concepts used in text-based programming languages.",H)])
add(g,s,1,3,[p("What is a bug in programming?","Code error.","An error in a program that causes it to behave incorrectly.",E),p("What is debugging?","Finding and fixing errors.","The process of finding and fixing bugs in a program.",E),p("A program is supposed to add two numbers but always outputs 0. What might be wrong?","Check the logic.","Variables might not be set correctly, or the addition step might be missing or overwritten.",M),p("What is the first step when a program doesn't work as expected?","Reproduce the bug.","Reproduce the error, then trace the code step by step to find where the behavior goes wrong.",M),p("Explain two debugging strategies.","Systematic fixing.","1) Print intermediate values to check what's happening. 2) Comment out sections to isolate the problem.",H),p("A student's game sprite disappears immediately at start. List three possible causes and fixes.","Multiple hypotheses.","1) Sprite is hidden — add 'show' block. 2) Wrong starting position. 3) A 'delete clone' block runs at start — check event blocks.",H)])
add(g,s,1,4,[p("What is a project in Scratch?","Created program.","A complete program you build and can share — a game, animation, or interactive story.",E),p("What is the first step in creating a coding project?","Plan before coding.","Plan your idea — what will it do, who is it for, what will users see and do?",E),p("What is a sprite's costume in Scratch?","Appearance.","A costume is a visual appearance of a sprite — you can switch between costumes to create animation.",M),p("How do you make a Scratch game end when the player touches something?","Collision detection.","Use 'if touching [object]: stop all' or a game-over message.",M),p("Design a simple quiz game concept in Scratch: describe at least 3 features.","Plan the game.","1) Ask a question using 'ask' block. 2) Check answer with 'if' block. 3) Keep score with a variable. 4) End game after 5 questions.",H),p("What makes a good interactive project? List four design principles.","Design thinking.","Clear goal, user-friendly controls, visual feedback, appropriate difficulty, and fun/engaging experience.",H)])

